<section id="market-dynamics" class="reveal">
  <h2>A Booming Market with Uneven Gains</h2>
  <p>The global vaccine market, valued at $79.19 billion in 2024, is on track to hit $137.24 billion by 2033, growing at a compound annual rate of 6.3% (WHO, 2025). High-income countries dominate, accounting for 72% of the market’s financial value in 2023, while middle-income nations hold 24%, and pooled procurement for low-income settings represents just 4%.</p>
  <p>Tiered pricing systems aim to bridge this gap, offering lower costs to poorer nations through mechanisms like UNICEF and PAHO. Still, the disparity fuels criticism that the industry prioritizes wealthier markets, where profit margins are higher.</p>
  <p>COVID-19 vaccines, while a public health success, intensified this debate. High prices in wealthier nations strained healthcare budgets, even as manufacturers defended costs by citing R&D investments. The numbers suggest a complex balance, not a simple exploitation.</p>
</section>

