<section id="lobbying-influence" class="reveal">
  <h2>The Shadow of Influence</h2>
  <p>Pharmaceutical lobbying is a powerhouse, with expenditures reaching $227 million in the first half of 2025, on pace to exceed the industry’s record of $388 million for 2024 (WHO, 2025). These funds shape policy, secure favorable regulations, and protect market interests—a reality acknowledged even by industry advocates like PhRMA’s Mike Ybarra, who emphasized the science-based rigor of vaccine recommendations (March 2026 statement).</p>
  <p>This influence isn’t inherently corrupt, but it amplifies public skepticism. When billions in profits are at stake, every policy decision is scrutinized for bias, even when the underlying science, as the CDC asserts, supports vaccination’s social and economic benefits (CDC, August 2025).</p>
</section>

<section id="trust-gap" class="reveal">
  <h2>Why Trust Falters</h2>
  <p>The evidence for vaccines’ value is overwhelming—508 million illnesses prevented, $2.7 trillion saved, a return of $11 per dollar spent (MMWR, 2024). Yet, public perception often lags, mired in suspicion of pharmaceutical motives. The $137 billion market projection and $227 million lobbying spend don’t help, feeding narratives of profit over people (WHO, 2025).</p>
  <p>Access issues compound this. While tiered pricing exists, high costs in wealthier nations and uneven distribution globally create visible inequities. Add to this the echo chambers of misinformation, and even robust data struggles to cut through.</p>
  <p>Historical missteps—however rare—also linger in collective memory. The distrust isn’t baseless; it’s just disproportionately weighted against the evidence of benefit.</p>
</section>

<aside class="pull-quote reveal"><p>“The evidence for vaccines’ value is overwhelming, yet public suspicion of pharmaceutical motives persists.”</p></aside>

<section id="path-forward" class="reveal">
  <h2>What Now?</h2>
  <p>Vaccines save lives and economies on a scale few interventions can match. The data—$2.7 trillion in societal savings, $11 returned per dollar, over 1 million deaths averted—stands as a monument to their worth (MMWR, 2024). Simultaneously, the financial machinery behind them, from $886.8 million development costs to a $137 billion market, invites scrutiny that no amount of public health success can fully deflect (ASPE, 2024; WHO, 2025).</p>
  <p>If the numbers are this clear, what will it take to rebuild trust in a system where profit and public good are so deeply intertwined? That question remains unanswered, hanging over every policy debate and every shot administered.</p>
</section>

